      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "All three FEA codes (FDA in-house, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) operate under documented software quality plans with version control, regression testing, and change management procedures consistent with Gradation 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "Each code has been verified against published benchmark problems and analytical solutions for linear elastic structural mechanics. Patch test and cantilever beam benchmarks are documented in the respective verification reports."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence studies were performed for all three models with at least three mesh refinement levels. The Richardson extrapolation-based GCI was computed and found below 5% for the primary quantity of interest (construct stiffness), exceeding the required Gradation 2 threshold."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "Default solver tolerances were tightened by one order of magnitude and residual convergence was confirmed for all load steps. Iterative solver residuals are reported in the analysis logs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "Model setup was independently reviewed by a second analyst at each institution. Boundary conditions, material assignments, and load application were verified against the simulation protocol prior to execution."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic continuum mechanics is appropriate for the sub-yield loading regime of the ASTM F1717 protocol. Contact mechanics at the screw-rod interface is modeled with frictional contact elements. Model form assumptions are documented and justified against the physical regime of interest."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "Material properties (Ti-6Al-4V: E=114 GPa, nu=0.34) were sourced from peer-reviewed literature and manufacturer data sheets. Geometric dimensions were measured from physical specimens using calibrated CMM with traceability to NIST standards."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "N=11 production pedicle screw constructs from the same lot were tested. Sample characterization included dimensional inspection and material certification. Sample size is consistent with ASTM F1717 requirements and supports statistical comparison."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single load condition (compression-bending at 5 degrees) per ASTM F1717. The absence of additional load conditions (e.g., torsion, lateral bending) limits the breadth of validation evidence. This factor falls below the required level and represents a known gap acknowledged in the credibility assessment."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "FEA boundary conditions were mapped directly to the physical test fixture geometry. Block separation distance, loading pin radius, and support conditions were replicated in the simulation to within measurement uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and failure load predictions were compared against experimental measurements using the validation metric (U95 interval) and the model-form uncertainty quantification approach. All three FEA models predicted stiffness within 10% of experimental mean; the ensemble mean bias is 3.2%."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness and peak load under ASTM F1717 compression-bending are the primary quantities of interest for the regulatory submission. These quantities directly inform the device's mechanical performance claims and are clinically relevant to lumbar spinal fixation safety."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Achieved level must meet or exceed required level for model risk level 3.",
      "rationale": "The validation scenario (ASTM F1717 static compression-bending of non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs) closely mirrors the intended regulatory use of the FEA model. The validation activities were designed a priori to support the specific claim that FEA can reliably predict construct mechanical performance for 510(k) submission purposes."
    }
  ],
